\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj\keepn\widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\cgrid {Introduction
\par }{\b0 This 
document is aimed at detailing some things about the fist of Xlevan clan. It incorporates the best ideas from all parties who have commented so far and is an attempt to consolidate the general consensus into an approved form for use as a reference.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par }{\fs24 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\qj\keepn\widctlpar\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\cgrid {Regional Control
\par }\pard\plain \s16\qj\widctlpar\adjustright \cgrid {
The fists do not control a HUGE area of land at this point in time. When compared with the theoretical dominion of the nobility east of the river, their holdings are actually quite small. What they do control consists of two main types of land:
\par 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls4\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls4\adjustright {
Wasteland, consisting of mountains, barren plains and bits of swamp. This land acts primarily as a buffer to the fists, with the only inhabitants typically being barely populated outposts and scouting stations. Whilst unimportant economically these l
ands are important strategically. Being sent to these outposts is often seen as a punishment amongst fist ranks. If any kind of attack was mounted, these lands would just be used to slow down progress more then anything before a proper defence could be mo
unted back in Cora\rquote Lyst itself. 
\par }\pard \s16\qj\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls4\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls4\adjustright {
Excellent farmland. Between the city and the wasteland buffer areas exists a large area of farmland which is a VERY valuable asset to the fists. This area typically consists of small farming communities. The fists suppl
y protection in terms of scouts and militias to these farmers in return for a valuable cut of the crops produced. This expanse of farmland ensures the Fists are self sufficient and do not rely on outside trade to account for food shortages.
\par }\pard \s16\qj\widctlpar\adjustright {
\par Rather then attempt to spread their dominion the fists have until now concentrated mainly on strengthening and consolidating their political and economic position. They have done this quite well, the importance of Cora\rquote 
Lyst to island-wide trade providing a great deal of funds, enough to support a large military which is then used to protect trade routes by road and sea alike. 
\par 
\par The success of Cora\rquote Lyst as a base of operations is largely due to its location and its government. The Traders Highway linking to Cora\rquote Tyl combined with its sea links with Il\rquote Cora\rquote 
Dvan make it a surprisingly convenient centre point for trade. Typically, direct links between Cora\rquote Tyl and Il\rquote Cora\rquote Dvan are uncommon, the roads more treacherous and less patrolled. Even though the threat of bandits is a
lways looming when passing through Falsta Tandar, typically a large enough escort / patrol will ensure safe passage. Along the northern roads, there are many more ambush points and no patrols to speak of. Some of the heavier and larger loads coming out of
 Cora\rquote Tyl just cannot be transported using the northern roads to Il\rquote Cora\rquote 
Dvan (due to the poor roads and the low weight capacity of the existing ferries). Rather then spend money on patrols, roads and ferries, the Silver Tongues are content with using Cora\rquote Lyst for now. The overall journey to get goods to Il\rquote Cora
\rquote Dvan is not much of a problem as the Silver Tongues have agents in Cora\rquote Lyst which effectively act as middle men, taking in Cora\rquote Tyl resources and selling them off from this point. It works out well
 for all parties, the fists and Cora\rquote Lyst become a central trading location, and the nobles / tongues do not need to spend revenue on new roads / improvements.
\par 
\par Since consolidating during Xlevan\rquote s time they have so far not acted to increase their domain, for a couple of good reasons:
\par 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls3\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls3\adjustright {
The consul wishes to preserve his/her authority over the clan. Whilst not at war the Consul is in charge, and would see no reason to alter things. 
\par }\pard \s16\qj\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls3\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls3\adjustright {
Much of the land close to their capital is not particularly rich land
 worth military and economic effort to obtain. Whilst they would indeed possess the strength there is the real possibility of stretching their resources too thinly and exposing themselves.
\par }\pard \s16\qj\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls3\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls3\adjustright {
Focusing on consolidating their capital has been particularly rewarding, the funds and political power available to them pretty substantial.
\par }\pard \s16\qj\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 4.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls3\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls3\adjustright {
They know all too well the problems east of the Tzan, with the large distances between holdings giving the ruling house of Seth\rquote o\rquote par some head aches in maintaining any type of control.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\fs24 
\par }\pard\plain \s16\qj\widctlpar\adjustright \cgrid {
This is not to say that thoughts of expansion are far from their minds. It is whispered amongst those in the know that the current commander is keen to expand the fists dominion, but is kept in check by the consul. I would hav
e no problem if when players start controlling the clan, this is changed and expansion becomes a priority. You can only consolidate for so long, and the larger and more skilled their military becomes the more restless unless kept occupied.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\fs24 
\par So far the fist
s have not mounted any MAJOR campaign against the bandits of Falsta Tandar or the privateers/pirates stronghold for fear of weakening themselves too greatly, but that is another agenda that is under advisement. For now the Fists are prepared to sit there,
 but it will be up to the players to decide the future direction of the clan. We can only school them in realistic directions and impose the right kinds of consequences / situations upon them based on their decisions.
\par 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\qj\keepn\widctlpar\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\cgrid {Racial Mix
\par }\pard\plain \s16\qj\widctlpar\adjustright \cgrid {This region is mainly populated by Rehan, especially the farmland. The city of course has a large mixture. There will also be a large amount of El\rquote 
Cvin, more so then any other city due to the close proximity of the western wilds and El\rquote Cvin communities. There are also a large number of Imolean considering the size of the port, and the necessity for many sailors etc \endash 
 many of these are Imolean. There are not many Malandrin or Cvin, though both races do have representation. Perhaps strange is that there are not too many Jlen either, f
or such a large city. This is likely as the Fists do not keep slaves. Most Jlen would live in the poorer section of the town (some thieves) or in the spill.
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\fs24 
\par There is no slavery in fist controlled areas, but the fists do place taxes upon the land they cont
rol. In return for the taxes paid the fists provide protection to even the most outlying of communities, with guards stationed in even small towns to protect against banditry and of course to impose fist law.
\par }\pard \qj\widctlpar\adjustright {\fs24 
\par Whilst there is no slavery within Cora\rquote Lyst th
e fists do not fight to abolish it, there just is none. They do not pretend to be a clan who strongly believe in freeing slaves and doing nobles deeds etc, they just respect and recognise that their clan was founded by the help of many slaves. They have a
l
so come to the realisation that having no slaves is good for employment and revenue, as those who might typically use slaves are often forced to hire locals to perform their work. Those attempting to trade slaves are quickly shown the door. When I say non
e, there is some leniency given for visiting diplomats of course. But if you live in Cora\rquote Lyst you cannot keep slaves, you will have to hire help from the local pool of talent.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {\fs24 
\par }\pard \qj\widctlpar\adjustright {\b\fs24 
\par Political Structure:}{\fs24  
\par Cora\rquote Lyst being the capital of the Fist territories, it obviously adopts the political hierarchy prescribed by the fists themselves, which is as follows:
\par 
\par The overseer of the city is the Fist\rquote s Consul. He is ultimately responsible for the political aspirations of the clan, and his is the name that rules Cora\rquote Ly
st of behalf of the fists. In matters of politics, economy and so forth he runs the clan. At his right hand and as virtual equal is the High Commander of the Fists armies. In times of war the High Commander has the authority to overrule the Consul\rquote 
s decisions and direct fist efforts as he sees fit. This is to ensure that all possible can be done to ensure the safety of the clan and the city.
\par 
\par It is in the best interests of the Consul one would believe to keep the clan OUT of war. Why? To preserve his/her au
thority. Meanwhile it is obviously not a foreign thought for the Commander to be seeking conflict / war. This elevates him/her to numero uno. This is something the players will need to work out. Perhaps they will not aspire to subject the realm into turmo
il based on their own power hungry aspirations or maybe they will.
\par 
\par Beneath the Consul is a large council of advisors. Their advice ranges from the economy, to the clans treasury, to various other influential and knowledgeable figures within the city and cl
an. These advisors have their own agents beneath them also, for example the harbor master, has a host of underlings to collect taxes and organise things, he/she doesn\rquote 
t just do it by themselves. Other advisors include the treasurer, the head of economy, the high commander (in times of non-war) and more.
\par 
\par Beneath the High Commander are a number of generals, each (like the high commander) with an estate in the inner city. The generals have various companies of men assigned to their command, and beneath them; 
the Captains train and order these men based on the Generals and ultimately High Commanders instructions. There is obviously competition amongst the Generals, and the Captains, to impress those higher up in the hierarchy. Specifically these generals are:

\par 
\par }\pard \qj\li720\widctlpar\adjustright {\i\fs24 General 1}{\fs24  \endash  In charge of the city protection, he has under him the captain of the city watch, the city guards, the jails, and the elite guard for the consul himself.
\par 
\par }{\i\fs24 General 2}{\fs24  \endash  In charge of port and navy interests, he and his captains control the navy and the port.
\par 
\par }{\i\fs24 General 3 and 4}{\fs24  \endash  Field generals, each with a host of men and captains to control. They
 control the majority of the Fists actual armies, cavalry, foot, archers etc. They would work in conjunction with general 1 in any defence of the city from outside attack.
\par 
\par }{\i\fs24 General 5}{\fs24  \endash  In charge of scouting parties and information retrieval. He would have 
agents and perhaps even a spy ring in various major centres. Maybe no one even knows he exists. We can talk about that. His underling captains would be spread throughout the island perhaps.
\par 
\par }{\i\fs24 General 6}{\fs24  \endash  In charge of highway patrols and protection and monit
oring of rurally controlled Fist centres outside the city but within Fist controlled lands. They are stationed at the far-flung outposts, but also see most of the action from bandits along the roads.
\par }\pard \qj\widctlpar\adjustright {\fs24 
\par The captains beneath these generals vary obviously base
d on the tasks they perform.  Each Generals section is split up in the military sector and each with its own name. So each captain controls a barracks in their Generals sector (typically). Training beneath the Captains and living mostly in the barracks ar
e the Sword Wielders, Shield Bearers, Bannermen and Recruits of the Fist clan.
\par 
