\par }{\b\fs24 Attitudes
\par }{\fs24 
\par Obviously there are a number of different parts to the social structure of the city as a whole, and the attitudes of these parts are quite important to describe. I would suggest the following attitudes:
\par 
\par The first thing is that there is variety, any attitude is possible, despite what I am suggesting is typical. I will explain.
\par 
\par Some of the soldiers for example would look down upon the common man, sneer and jibe at their expense. This would not be the global case, as some of the soldiers have wives and children
 and friends amongst the common man. Typically soldiers are well disciplined and mannered even whilst outside their training areas. Of course this is not always the case, some soldiers notorious for their drinking, whoring and wenching in the brothels and
 taverns in the poorer part of time when off duty.
\par 
\par Typically the common man respects the soldiers and their place within the city, they would nod their heads in greeting and offer any information requested to them. Once again this is not always the case, s
ome of those in the poorer section despising the soldiers (maybe because they are thieves).
\par 
\par Typically the wealthy steer clear of the poorer parts of town, and often even the markets, sending lackeys to purchase whatever wares they need. They are often arr
ogant people. Some of the wealthy do not believe in mixing with the commoners and even look down on the soldiers as brutes and what have you. This depends on the individual once again, the occasional merchant walking amongst the commoners and drinking / w
enching in the poorer section from time to time.
\par 
\par Some advisors would by sycophantic, others more real when it comes to giving advice to the consul. Most would be highly ambitious and motivated.
\par 
\par Basically people tend to respect those more powerful / wealth
y / influential then they, and the general demeanor of the people is a content one. But as I have mentioned above there is not set way in which the various facets of society must act, except of course to respect the law and not piss off a real high ranker
 (i.e. a general of the consul himself!). As for titles of address, in military circles, soldiers would address higher ranking officers with a sir prefix, with a few exceptions:
\par 
\par - The High Commander would be addressed as High Commander blah.
\par - The Consul similarly addressed as Consul blah.
\par Both are esteemed titles and mean close to what High Prince does in the nobility of Il\rquote Cora\rquote Dvan.
\par 
\par Generals would be addressed as Lord General blah by underlings.
\par Captains addressed as Captain blah or sir.
\par Captains or Generals would address their underlings by their rank, as in \ldblquote Bannerman Smith, stand to attention!\rdblquote  Or \ldblquote Shield Bearer, face front!\rdblquote 
\par 
\par Commoners would not use the sir prefix when addressing military ranks, but they would be respectful, as in \ldblquote Yes Captain, I will do as you suggest\rdblquote .
\par 
